  "final_answer": "## Analysis: What Can Be Determined vs. What Requires Amendment\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 filed May 20, 2026 is a preliminary \"Subject to Completion\" filing. The cover page, prospectus summary, capitalization table, and beneficial ownership table all leave the number of Class A shares offered, the IPO price range, and all post-IPO ownership and voting figures as redacted blanks. The filing states it will become effective only upon a further amendment under Section 8(a) of the Securities Act. Below is the analysis for each item:\n\n---\n\n### (i) Post-IPO Fully Diluted Share Count — **Requires Amendment Disclosure**\n\n**Cannot be determined from the filing as filed.** Three interdependent blanks prevent calculation:\n\n1. **Number of shares offered is blank.** Every instance — the cover page, prospectus summary, capitalization table, dilution table, and underwriting section — uses the placeholder \"      shares.\" The fee table references 66,666,670 shares across escalating aggregate price tiers ($5.5 trillion to $7.5 trillion), but this appears to serve as a fee-calculation placeholder under Rule 457(o) rather than a finalized offering size; the cover page blanks confirm the number is not yet set.\n\n2. **Over-allotment (greenshoe) size is blank.** The underwriting section reads: \"up to ____ additional shares.\"\n\n3. **IPO price is blank.** Fully diluted share count requires the IPO price for the treasury stock method when counting in-the-money options and RSUs. The filing discloses pre-split dilutive securities (options, RSUs, future grant reserves) but post-split, post-IPO dilutive counts depend on the offering price.\n\nAdditionally, material contingent share issuances — Musk's 11 remaining earnout milestones (each 0.20% of fully diluted capitalization), the Cursor acquisition option ($60 billion in Class A stock), and the EchoStar spectrum consideration shares — all depend on post-IPO valuations and closing conditions not determinable from the preliminary filing.\n\n---\n\n### (ii) Class A Versus Class B Economic Ownership — **Requires Amendment Disclosure**\n\n**Cannot be precisely determined from the filing as filed.**\n\nThe pre-IPO pro forma share counts (after Class C reclassification, preferred conversion, 5-for-1 stock split, and xAI/X Holdings mergers) are disclosed:\n\n| Class | Pro Forma Shares Outstanding | Approximate Economic Ownership |\n|-------|------------------------------|-------------------------------|\n| Class A | 6,824,581,339 | ~54.5% |\n| Class B | 5,695,729,430 | ~45.5% |\n| **Total** | **12,520,310,769** | **100%** |\n\nClass A and Class B shares have identical economic rights (pro rata dividends, ratable liquidation). However, post-IPO, Class A outstanding will increase by the unknown number of shares sold to the public while Class B remains unchanged. The capitalization table's \"Pro Forma As Adjusted\" column leaves Class A shares outstanding blank. Without the final offering size, the post-IPO economic ownership split between Class A and Class B cannot be computed.\n\n---\n\n### (iii) Musk's Post-IPO Voting Control — **Partially Determinable**\n\n**Qualitative conclusion CAN be determined; exact percentage requires amendment.**\n\nThe filing explicitly and repeatedly states that immediately after the offering, Elon Musk will hold **more than 50% of the combined voting power** of outstanding common stock. This is disclosed as a definitive fact, not as forward-looking or conditional language. The filing further states SpaceX will qualify as a Nasdaq \"controlled company,\" exempting it from certain board independence requirements. Key supporting facts disclosed:\n\n- Musk beneficially owns **93.6%** of Class B shares (10 votes per share) pre-offering\n- Class B holders, voting separately, elect 51% of the board\n- Musk can only be removed as CEO/Chairman by a majority vote of Class B shares (which he controls)\n\nHowever, the **exact post-IPO voting percentage is redacted** — the prospectus uses blanks such as \"___%\" in every post-offering column of the beneficial ownership table and in the prospectus summary. Pre-offering, Musk's combined voting power is disclosed as **85.1%**.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Item | Determinable from Filing as Filed? | Requires Amendment? |\n|------|-------------------------------------|---------------------|\n| (i) Post-IPO fully diluted share count | **No** | **Yes** — offering size, greenshoe, and IPO price all blank |\n| (ii) Class A vs. Class B economic ownership | **No** (pre-IPO split is known: ~54.5%/45.5%, but post-IPO depends on blank offering size) | **Yes** |\n| (iii) Musk's post-IPO voting control | **Partially** — majority voting control (>50%) is affirmatively disclosed; exact percentage is **not** determinable | **Yes** (for the exact percentage) |\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n```json\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```",
